<paragraph blockId="53.[732,1329,278,701]" pageId="53" pageNumber="811">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[732,887,278,307]" pageId="53" pageNumber="811">Taxonomy.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Bobrinski, 1926" authorityName="Bobrinski" authorityYear="1926" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Eptesicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="53" pageNumber="811" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="alaschanicus">Eptesicus alaschanicus Bobrinski, 1926</taxonomicName>
, 
<materialsCitation pageId="53" pageNumber="811">
Hotin Gol Pass, Alashan Range, 
<collectingCountry box="[733,869,354,387]" name="Mongolia" pageId="53" pageNumber="811">Mongolia</collectingCountry>
.
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="53.[732,1329,278,701]" lastBlockId="53.[121,1332,708,2437]" pageId="53" pageNumber="811">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bobrinskii" baseAuthorityYear="1926" box="[734,1025,392,425]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Hypsugo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="53" pageNumber="811" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="alaschanicus">Hypsugo alaschanicus</taxonomicName>
is generally considered a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bonaparte" baseAuthorityYear="1837" box="[1025,1129,432,465]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Hypsugo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="53" pageNumber="811" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="savii">H. savii</taxonomicName>
, but morphological and genetic data support its species status; nevertheless, they are closely related genetically, and further work is needed to clarify their relationship. Taxa coreensis and velox are both considered synonyms of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bobrinskii" baseAuthorityYear="1926" box="[734,947,668,701]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Hypsugo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="53" pageNumber="811" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="alaschanicus">H. alaschanicus</taxonomicName>
here, although both may represent valid subspecies, based on limited morphological differences; the formeris occasionally treated as a distinct species. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
